    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "NMS tetrad: Fever + Rigidity (lead-pipe) + Altered Mental Status + Autonomic Instability (tachycardia, BP lability, diaphoresis)",
      "STOP the causative antipsychotic IMMEDIATELY — this is the most important step",
      "CK is typically markedly elevated (>1,000, often >10,000) from rhabdomyolysis",
      "Treatment: aggressive IV fluids (target UOP 200-300mL/hr), cooling measures, dantrolene (muscle relaxant) and/or bromocriptine (dopamine agonist)",
      "NMS develops over DAYS (unlike serotonin syndrome which develops over HOURS) — key timeline distinguisher",
      "ICU admission required — mortality is 10-20% even with treatment; complications include AKI, DIC, respiratory failure"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Serotonin Syndrome (clonus + myoclonus + hyperreflexia vs lead-pipe rigidity in NMS — DIFFERENT exam findings)",
      "Malignant Hyperthermia (anesthesia-related, similar but different trigger)",
      "Meningitis/Encephalitis (fever + altered mental status + neck stiffness — LP if any concern)",
      "Sepsis (fever + tachycardia + leukocytosis — overlapping features, must rule out)",
      "Lethal Catatonia (psychiatric emergency that can mimic NMS — treatment is benzodiazepines + ECT)",
      "Heat Stroke (environmental exposure, CNS dysfunction, but no rigidity)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Confusing NMS with serotonin syndrome — NMS has lead-pipe rigidity and NO clonus; SS has clonus, myoclonus, and hyperreflexia",
      "Missing the medication history — always ask about antipsychotic changes in any patient with rigidity and fever",
      "Continuing the antipsychotic because 'the patient needs it for their psych condition' — NMS is lethal, stop the drug",
      "Not checking CK — rhabdomyolysis is both diagnostic and the major cause of morbidity (AKI)",
      "Inadequate fluid resuscitation — these patients need massive volumes to prevent myoglobin-induced renal failure",
      "Attributing fever to infection without considering NMS in patients on antipsychotics",
      "Missing hyperkalemia from rhabdomyolysis — can cause fatal arrhythmia"
    ],
