    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Beck's Triad of tamponade: hypotension + muffled heart sounds + JVD — present in only ~30% of cases but pathognomonic when complete",
      "POCUS is the DIAGNOSTIC TOOL — RA diastolic collapse is the earliest and most sensitive echo sign of tamponade physiology",
      "Pulsus paradoxus >10mmHg = tamponade. Measure: inflate cuff to obliterate all Korotkoff sounds, slowly deflate — first sound heard only in expiration, continue deflating until sounds heard throughout cycle. Difference >10mmHg = positive.",
      "PERICARDIOCENTESIS is the treatment — subxiphoid approach under echo guidance. Removing even 50mL can dramatically improve hemodynamics.",
      "Malignant effusions: lung cancer is the #1 cause. Pericardiocentesis provides diagnosis (cytology) and treatment. Recurrence is common — may need pericardial window.",
      "Tamponade is an OBSTRUCTIVE SHOCK — do NOT give diuretics (reduces preload further) or intubate if possible (positive pressure reduces preload)"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Tension pneumothorax (also causes obstructive shock with JVD and hypotension — but absent breath sounds and tracheal deviation differentiate)",
      "Massive PE (obstructive shock with JVD — but ECHO shows RV dilation rather than pericardial fluid)",
      "Acute MI with cardiogenic shock (different ECHO findings — wall motion abnormalities, no effusion unless post-MI rupture)",
      "Constrictive pericarditis (chronic symptoms with diastolic heart failure — different from acute tamponade)",
      "Aortic dissection with hemopericardium (Type A dissection bleeding into pericardium — needs OR, not just pericardiocentesis)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Intubating the patient — positive pressure ventilation reduces preload and can cause cardiac arrest in tamponade. If intubation is absolutely necessary, give IV fluids simultaneously.",
      "Giving diuretics — tamponade is a preload-dependent state. Diuresis reduces preload and worsens hypotension.",
      "Not checking for pulsus paradoxus — it's easy to measure and highly suggestive",
      "Waiting for cardiology to arrive before performing pericardiocentesis in an unstable patient — if the patient is crashing, emergent bedside drainage is indicated",
      "Not sending pericardial fluid for cytology — this may be the first diagnosis of cancer or confirm metastatic disease",
      "Assuming effusion = tamponade — size doesn't determine tamponade; RATE of accumulation determines hemodynamic impact. Slow effusions can be massive without tamponade; rapid effusions can cause tamponade with small volumes."
    ],
