    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "HYPERKALEMIA ECG PROGRESSION: peaked T waves → prolonged PR → widened QRS → loss of P waves → sine wave → VFib/asystole. Treat based on ECG changes, not just the number.",
      "TREATMENT ORDER for severe hyperkalemia: (1) CALCIUM GLUCONATE 10% — 10mL IV over 2-3 minutes (membrane stabilizer — does NOT lower K, but protects the heart; onset seconds), (2) INSULIN 10 units regular + D50 50mL IV (shifts K intracellularly; onset 15-30 min), (3) ALBUTEROL nebulizer 10-20mg (shifts K intracellularly; onset 15-30 min), (4) SODIUM BICARBONATE if acidotic (shifts K; onset 30-60 min), (5) KAYEXALATE or patiromer (removes K from body; onset hours), (6) EMERGENT DIALYSIS (definitive removal of K in ESRD patients)",
      "Calcium gluconate DOES NOT LOWER potassium — it stabilizes the cardiac membrane. Must follow with therapies that actually shift or remove potassium.",
      "This patient's medications are CONTRIBUTING: ACE-I (lisinopril) blocks aldosterone → reduces K excretion. Spironolactone is potassium-SPARING. In ESRD, these medications dramatically worsen hyperkalemia.",
      "EMERGENT DIALYSIS is the definitive treatment for hyperkalemia in ESRD — call nephrology immediately and arrange access (AV fistula is functioning)",
      "Repeat ECG after calcium gluconate to confirm improvement — if sine wave persists, repeat calcium dose"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Cardiac arrest (sine wave → VFib or asystole — have defibrillator ready and give calcium gluconate STAT)",
      "Hypoglycemia from insulin treatment (always give D50 WITH insulin — check glucose every 30 minutes after insulin)",
      "Hypervolemia/pulmonary edema (missed dialysis = fluid overload — may need emergent dialysis for both K and volume)",
      "Medication contribution (stop ACE-I and spironolactone — both potassium-retaining in ESRD)",
      "Concurrent metabolic acidosis (bicarb 14 — acidosis drives potassium extracellularly; correction helps lower K)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Waiting for lab results before treating — if ECG shows peaked T waves or worse, give calcium gluconate IMMEDIATELY while awaiting potassium level",
      "Giving insulin without dextrose — will cause hypoglycemia (potentially fatal). ALWAYS pair 10 units regular insulin with 1 amp D50.",
      "Using only potassium-shifting agents without definitive removal — insulin, albuterol, and bicarb only SHIFT potassium temporarily. In ESRD, dialysis is the only way to actually remove it.",
      "Not checking the ECG FIRST — the ECG determines urgency, not the potassium number. A K of 6.8 without ECG changes is less emergent than K of 6.5 WITH widened QRS.",
      "Forgetting to recheck potassium — after treatment, K must be monitored every 1-2 hours because shifting agents wear off (insulin effect ~4-6 hours)",
      "Not discontinuing offending medications — ACE-I + spironolactone in this patient are contributing to hyperkalemia and must be stopped"
    ],
